article.description:
Jason Williams scored 28 points and handed out 14 assists Monday night as the Memphis Grizzlies turned back a
second-half comeback by New Orleans and defeated the Hornets 106-102.
article.headline: This time, Grizzlies don't lose after 30-plus point lead
article.linkText: Grizzlies blow big lead, but hold on to top Hornets
article.story:
MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) -- The Memphis Grizzlies have a strange problem -- they can't hold 30-point leads.
Williams

The Grizzlies led New Orleans by 31 points with 6:47 left in third quarter Monday night, let the Hornets get within one with less than three minutes left in the game and finally held on to win 106-102. It marked the second consecutive game in which the Grizzlies almost blew a lead of more than 30 points. On Friday, Memphis squandered a 32-point lead against the Los Angeles Clippers before recovering to win. "It's a good problem to have,'' Memphis forward Shane Battier said. "I'd rather be talking about losing a 30-point lead than trying to come back from 30 down.'' Jason Williams scored 28 points and handed out 14 assists as the Grizzlies turned back the second-half New Orleans comeback. "I tell people all the time, it might be safer to have a 5- or a 10-point lead as opposed to a 30-point lead,'' Williams said. "I don't care who you are, you are going to relax a little bit. But we have to fight through it and overcome it.'' The Hornets got within one, 97-96, when Courtney Alexander hit a 12-foot turnaround with 2:51 to play. But they could never overtake the Grizzlies as Williams hit two shots to extend the Memphis lead and sealed the win with two free throws with just under 24 seconds to play. "I feel like my shot is going to go in every time I shoot it,'' Williams said. "I've just got to take my time, take good shots and try not to rush things.'' The Grizzlies led 76-45 when Battier made a 3-pointer with 6:47 remaining in the third. The Hornets then outscored Memphis 23-6 in the rest of the quarter to cut the lead to 82-68. A pair of early 3-pointers by David Wesley and Jamal Mashburn fueled a 14-5 Hornets' run to open the quarter and get New Orleans within five, 87-82. "We just waited too late to make the run,'' said Hornets coach Paul Silas. "If we had tied the score, I feel as if we would have had a chance to win. I looked at the tape of the (Clippers) game, and they were down by over 30 and almost won,'' he said. "So, I knew they would give (the lead) up.'' The win was Memphis' second straight and their eighth in the last nine home games. The loss snapped a two-game winning streak for New Orleans, but the Hornets have lost nine of their last 12. Williams was 10-of-17 from the field as Memphis shot 51 percent to overcome 18 turnovers. Pau Gasol added 24 for the Grizzlies, and Lorenzen Wright had 20 and grabbed 14 rebounds. Mashburn led New Orleans with 30 points, including 24 in the second half, and had 11 assists. Wesley finished with 18, while Alexander and Robert Traylor had 10 each. The Grizzlies led 58-36 at the half, thanks to a 54.5 percent shooting performance from the field. Williams and Gasol led Memphis with 16 points each, each hitting 6-of-9 shots. Memphis built its lead in the second quarter, outscoring the Hornets 28-12. "I never felt like we were done. It was just too far back to have that final push at the end,'' Wesley said. But Mashburn said the difference is the Grizzlies' play under Hubie Brown. Memphis, which lost its first 13 games of the season, is 11-14 since Brown took over for Sidney Lowe. "He has given this team a different look,'' Mashburn said. "The Grizzlies of old wouldn't have had that kind of lead on us.''

Game notes
Baron Davis, the Hornets' second-leading scorer, sat out his second consecutive game with back spasms. Alexander started in his place. "It's awfully tough to play without your main guy,'' Silas said. ... Memphis guard Brevin Knight missed the game because of gastritis. ... The Grizzlies are now 10-9 at home for the season, the first time the franchise has been above .500 at home this late in the season. ... Williams' 14 assists was a season high. Mashburn's 11 assists also was a season high. ... Mashburn has led the Hornets in scoring the last five games. ... P.J. Brown, the league's fourth-best shooter at 52.7 percent, connected on only 2-of-7 from the field. ... The Hornets were playing their third game in four days.
